diff:1619318430:1618113294:=77,85c77%0a%3c #foxbegin 210425-024031-932320#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Additional variations of "Turn the light off" in Indian English %0a%3c -> - AnanyaV%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c In Indian English, it is also common to use the phrase "off the light" instead of "turn off the light". Similarly, "on the light" is often used in place of "turn on the light". As in the translation you gave, this could be because most Indian languages do not include a word for "turn" when forming the phrase "turn off/on the light", so the Indian English variant of this phrase ends up omitting 'turn' altogether. %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210425-024031-932320#%0a---%0a> %0a
